21:29.422 --> 21:31.172
(PHONE VIBRATES)

21:35.339 --> 21:37.881
-Holly Gibney.
-Hey, Holly, it's Alec Pelley.

21:37.964 --> 21:39.255
HOLLY: Hello, Alec Pelley.

21:39.339 --> 21:40.714
ALEC:
Nice to hear your voice again.

21:40.798 --> 21:42.923
HOLLY: It's nice to hear
your voice again, too.

21:43.005 --> 21:46.798
ALEC: I guess I'll cut right
to the chase here, um...

21:46.881 --> 21:50.506
A man was arrested down here
by local PD...

21:50.589 --> 21:53.381
for the rape and murder
of an 11-year-old boy,

21:54.422 --> 21:55.339
but...

21:55.422 --> 21:56.923
there's still some question
as to whether

21:57.005 --> 21:58.381
they collared the right guy.

21:58.673 --> 21:59.881
And...

21:59.964 --> 22:02.422
answering that involves
backchecking a trip

22:02.506 --> 22:06.506
he made to Dayton Ohio
with his family in early March.

22:06.589 --> 22:09.923
Does that, uh... That sound like
a piece of cake to you?

22:10.005 --> 22:11.464
HOLLY:
Who was the arresting officer?

22:11.547 --> 22:12.964
ALEC: Ralph Anderson.

22:13.047 --> 22:15.047
HOLLY: Well, I'm not agreeing
to anything over the phone.

22:15.130 --> 22:17.631
-ALEC: Okay... Why's that?
-Because the last time

22:17.714 --> 22:19.964
I committed to a job that way,
it turned out that the man

22:20.047 --> 22:21.923
who hired me had a swastika
tattooed on his forehead

22:22.005 --> 22:23.255
and I didn't discover that

22:23.339 --> 22:26.255
until I turned up at his house
with his runaway daughter.

22:26.339 --> 22:28.589
So, if he wants me to be part
of his investigation,

22:28.673 --> 22:30.881
-he has to see me face to face.
-Okay.

22:30.964 --> 22:32.673
Well, I guess I can talk
to Howie,

22:32.756 --> 22:33.798
maybe fly you down here.

22:33.881 --> 22:35.506
HOLLY: Well, as you know,
I'm an aviophobic.

22:35.589 --> 22:37.172
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

22:37.255 --> 22:38.381
ALEC: You're what?

22:40.047 --> 22:41.422
You're sitting in my seat.

22:44.130 --> 22:45.047
ALEC: Hello?

22:45.130 --> 22:46.589
MAN: Miss, do you see
the other stools.

22:48.839 --> 22:50.714
You're okay where you are,
but you...

22:51.464 --> 22:52.881
you're sitting in my seat.

22:59.589 --> 23:00.631
Thank you.

23:02.464 --> 23:04.714
ALEC: Holly? You still there?

23:04.798 --> 23:05.881
Yes, I'm still here.

23:05.964 --> 23:07.547
What was that you just
called yourself?

23:07.631 --> 23:09.089
-I'm not flying.
-Okay.

23:09.172 --> 23:10.297
(PHONE BEEPS)

23:12.964 --> 23:15.089
-Okay.
-(PHONE BEEPS)

23:15.923 --> 23:18.798
(INDISTINCT CHATTER FROM TV)

23:30.714 --> 23:32.005
RALPH: Oldest trick in the book.

23:33.714 --> 23:35.089
HERB ZUCKER: What's that?

23:37.631 --> 23:40.339
RALPH: (SCOFFS)
I know what you're doing, you...

23:40.422 --> 23:41.464
(INHALES SHARPLY)

23:42.714 --> 23:45.756
So, you have a bad actor
with you in the box, right?

23:45.839 --> 23:49.297
And he thinks he's finished
answering all your questions,

23:50.089 --> 23:51.673
all you gotta do is sit there.

23:53.381 --> 23:54.464
Say nothing.

23:56.255 --> 23:59.214
Before you know it,
he gets nervous,

23:59.297 --> 24:01.297
starts talking and then
you got him,

24:01.381 --> 24:03.547
because you got him going past
his rehearsed answers.

24:07.798 --> 24:09.255
HERB: So...

24:09.339 --> 24:11.881
how have you been spending your
time since our last session?

24:12.547 --> 24:13.839
RALPH: Chores, mostly.

24:13.923 --> 24:14.923
HERB: What kind of chores?

24:15.005 --> 24:16.547
RALPH: You know, gardening,
yard work, cars.

24:16.631 --> 24:19.798
I hear that physical activity
is its own kind of therapy.

24:25.673 --> 24:27.089
How are things at home?

24:28.047 --> 24:29.297
RALPH: Um...

24:29.381 --> 24:31.673
-Home?
-With your wife?

24:31.756 --> 24:35.214
Oh. (MURMURS)
We're good. We're always good.

24:37.214 --> 24:39.172
I mean, you know...

24:41.631 --> 24:43.381
There was a time,
you know, when...

24:45.047 --> 24:47.631
Well, I guess, you know,
I wasn't so sure,

24:47.714 --> 24:49.756
we were going to make it.
Maybe for...

24:49.839 --> 24:51.923
about six months or so, but...

24:52.005 --> 24:54.714
we made it and, uh, we're good.

24:56.964 --> 24:58.089
What was going on?

25:00.714 --> 25:02.422
Um... Losing a child.

25:06.923 --> 25:08.214
Our only child.

25:09.547 --> 25:11.214
And I guess that, uh...

25:13.422 --> 25:15.297
something like that's either
going to...

25:15.381 --> 25:18.964
bring you closer than you ever
been or, uh, it's gonna...

25:21.089 --> 25:23.631
It's, uh...
It'll tear you apart and...

25:26.756 --> 25:28.422
I've seen it happens both ways.

25:30.255 --> 25:31.255
I'm sorry.

25:32.130 --> 25:34.339
No, like I said,
we got through it.

25:34.422 --> 25:35.631
We're good.

25:38.047 --> 25:41.255
What was it like for you
when things were still rough?

25:44.923 --> 25:47.964
(INAUDIBLE)

26:04.547 --> 26:06.589
(GRUNTING)

26:10.297 --> 26:11.339
(YELLING)

26:14.214 --> 26:15.923
(GRUNTING)

26:17.756 --> 26:21.673
(GRUNTING)

26:33.297 --> 26:36.297
Maybe we could just keep it
about the things that actually

26:36.381 --> 26:37.506
put me in this chair.

26:39.464 --> 26:41.589
♪ (OMINOUS MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

26:41.673 --> 26:43.381
(DOG BARKING)

27:05.631 --> 27:08.964
(COMMENTATOR SPEAKS
INDISTINCTLY)

27:11.798 --> 27:12.964
ALEC: You know,
the first game

27:13.047 --> 27:15.172
my dad ever took me
to was at Wrigley.

27:16.297 --> 27:18.047
1985, Cubbies-Mets.

27:18.130 --> 27:21.381
Must have been towards the end
of the season somewhere, but...

27:22.381 --> 27:23.464
after all these years

27:23.547 --> 27:26.005
-who can remember the date.
-Did they win or lose?

27:27.381 --> 27:28.381
Cubbies lost.

27:29.339 --> 27:33.381
-September 26th.
-Mm. September 26th?

27:35.255 --> 27:36.798
I wish I could remember
who was pitching.

27:36.881 --> 27:38.339
Johnny Abrego started
for the Cubs,

27:38.422 --> 27:40.172
but was knocked out
on the fourth.

27:40.255 --> 27:43.714
He was relieved by Ron Meredith,
Steve Engel and Jay Baller.

27:43.798 --> 27:44.923
Dwight Gooden,
on the other hand,

27:45.005 --> 27:46.839
threw a complete game shutout
for the Mets.

27:47.464 --> 27:48.714
(ALEC CHUCKLES)

27:50.172 --> 27:52.714
Hello, Alec, who's your friend?

27:57.964 --> 27:59.714
I'm gonna need the name
and address of the hotel

27:59.798 --> 28:01.172
that the family
were staying in in Dayton.

28:01.255 --> 28:02.673
-RALPH: It's in there.
-And the room number?

28:02.756 --> 28:03.881
RALPH: I can get that for you.

28:03.964 --> 28:06.255
I'm gonna need the location of
the parking lot

28:06.339 --> 28:08.547
-and the restaurant.
-It's in there.

28:08.631 --> 28:11.589
The hospital information
I can see...

28:12.714 --> 28:16.714
(MUTTERS)
Father's medical records?

28:17.964 --> 28:19.047
I need that.

28:19.631 --> 28:21.297
No.

28:21.381 --> 28:24.631
I need to find out who was
working in that wing...

28:24.714 --> 28:26.297
the days of
the Maitlands' visits.

28:27.172 --> 28:28.297
That's my job.

28:29.756 --> 28:32.005
I'm gonna need a thousand
in cash, 20s and 50s,

28:32.089 --> 28:33.339
all of which
will be accounted for,

28:33.422 --> 28:34.339
and if I don't use it

28:34.422 --> 28:35.798
you can just deduct it
from my fee.

28:35.881 --> 28:37.589
-ALEC: That's no problem.
-Speaking of my fee,

28:37.673 --> 28:40.005
-I'm gonna need half.
-That's no problem either.

28:41.798 --> 28:43.464
-WAITER: Here you go.
-Done and done.

28:45.839 --> 28:46.923
Insvekataj!

28:47.964 --> 28:51.881
It-- It means, uh,
"For your health" in Lithuanian.

28:51.964 --> 28:54.172
-RALPH: Oh, right.
-And then you say, "Insvekataj!"

28:55.047 --> 28:56.047
-Right.
-Yeah.

28:56.130 --> 28:57.172
Insvekataj.

29:08.631 --> 29:09.631
Hey.

29:11.172 --> 29:13.506
I-- I thought they screened
our mail for things like this.

29:14.422 --> 29:15.506
Must have slipped through.

29:16.631 --> 29:18.547
(INDISTINCT CHATTER)

29:37.255 --> 29:39.589
HOLLY: I have to say all these
contradicting eyewits,

29:39.673 --> 29:41.255
videos and forensics,

29:41.339 --> 29:44.130
sounds like your man has, uh,
a doppelgänger.

29:48.631 --> 29:50.964
From the German, uh,
"double goer."

29:51.047 --> 29:54.172
The myth is...
if it's a myth, is that, uh,

29:54.255 --> 29:57.923
everyone in the world has, uh,
an identical double.

29:58.005 --> 30:00.464
If you mean by that a twin,
we've already checked that out.

30:00.547 --> 30:03.255
Not a twin. No, no, sir.
Um...

30:03.339 --> 30:06.339
a non-biological double.

30:06.422 --> 30:10.297
The Egyptians call it a "Ka,"
the Norwegians a "Vardoger,"

30:10.381 --> 30:12.464
the Finns an "Etainen,"

30:12.547 --> 30:15.422
-the Swiss a "Dark Uncle"--
-She likes history.

30:15.506 --> 30:17.464
HOLLY:
My particular favorite is...

30:17.547 --> 30:19.130
"Fetch," uh,
from the Old Irish.

30:19.214 --> 30:20.130
(CHUCKLES)

30:20.214 --> 30:23.297
Find that word quite fetching,
don't you?

30:23.381 --> 30:27.964
What we're looking for is, uh...
is flesh and blood male biped.

30:28.047 --> 30:29.172
(RALPH CLEARS THROAT)

30:29.255 --> 30:31.714
My theory about the doppelgänger
is that it is, uh,

30:31.798 --> 30:35.089
a primitive construct they used
to explain bi-polar disorder,

30:35.172 --> 30:37.464
or schizophrenia, or just
the everyday struggle between

30:37.547 --> 30:39.547
-the id and the super-ego--
-If it's a myth?

30:42.297 --> 30:45.089
-What?
-You said, "if" it's a myth.

30:45.839 --> 30:47.381
-Yes, I did.
-RALPH: Mm.

30:47.464 --> 30:49.506
Because I have no, um...

30:49.589 --> 30:51.381
tolerance for the unexplainable.

31:03.923 --> 31:05.089
Well then, sir...

31:06.422 --> 31:08.798
you'll have no tolerance for me.

31:08.881 --> 31:10.422
Okay, here we go...

31:11.756 --> 31:12.923
I can tell you what day

31:13.005 --> 31:15.255
May 1st lands on
204 years from now

31:15.339 --> 31:17.005
faster than
any computer on Earth.

31:17.089 --> 31:19.631
I can look at a skyscraper for
two seconds from a speeding car

31:19.714 --> 31:22.339
and tell you within six inches
how tall that building is.

31:22.422 --> 31:24.756
And I can not only recite
the lyrics of every

31:24.839 --> 31:27.839
rock and roll song written from
1954 to the present day,

31:27.923 --> 31:29.506
but I can tell you which
Billboard chart position

31:29.589 --> 31:31.964
they were in week to week
until it fell off completely,

31:32.047 --> 31:33.130
but you know what?

31:34.964 --> 31:37.255
I don't listen to music,
because I don't like it.

31:39.172 --> 31:40.714
Heights make me throw up.

31:40.798 --> 31:42.547
And if you ask me what date
it is today,

31:42.631 --> 31:43.881
I have to look at a calendar.

31:43.964 --> 31:45.881
-Now, all that's true, brother--
-When I was four years old

31:45.964 --> 31:48.839
my parents took me to see
a psychiatrist to be examined.

31:48.923 --> 31:50.547
That was what got
the ball rolling.

31:50.631 --> 31:52.547
And, well, by the time
I was eight years old,

31:52.631 --> 31:53.798
I had been tested,

31:53.881 --> 31:57.923
uh, studied, uh, written about
and videoed by...

31:58.005 --> 31:59.964
psychiatrists, behaviorists,

32:00.047 --> 32:01.714
neuroscientists
and six different kinds

32:01.798 --> 32:03.506
of interdisciplinary
socio-biologists,

32:03.589 --> 32:04.839
and you know what they said?

32:05.756 --> 32:06.839
"Fuck if I know."

32:09.547 --> 32:10.756
So...

32:10.839 --> 32:11.964
Mr. Anderson...

32:13.923 --> 32:16.798
if I feel like using
the conditional "if"...

32:18.923 --> 32:20.839
then "if" is the word,
mockingbird.

32:25.631 --> 32:28.130
Your parents allowed them
to do that to you?

32:35.089 --> 32:36.172
They were scared.

32:39.881 --> 32:41.964
They thought the white coats
could cure me.

32:45.756 --> 32:47.589
Cure you of being yourself?

32:54.714 --> 32:56.381
I think I need to go upstairs.

32:57.506 --> 32:59.881
-Can I help you with anything?
-HOLLY: I'm good.

33:03.673 --> 33:04.923
You don't like to drink
that much,

33:05.005 --> 33:06.923
but you did it to make me
feel comfortable.

33:07.798 --> 33:08.839
Thank you.

33:15.214 --> 33:19.547
(DOOR OPENS, CLOSES)

33:23.964 --> 33:26.714
(BREATHES HEAVILY)

33:49.255 --> 33:50.923
(EXHALES CALMLY)

33:54.089 --> 33:55.381
(GROANS)

34:07.297 --> 34:09.756
(BREATHES SHARPLY)

34:14.714 --> 34:17.964
(WINCES)

35:40.464 --> 35:41.506
Honey, what's wrong?

35:41.589 --> 35:44.714
You need to call that detective
that hurt my dad.

35:44.798 --> 35:48.297
-Who? Ralph Anderson?
-I don't know his name.

35:48.381 --> 35:50.255
-The sad-looking one.
-Why?

35:50.339 --> 35:52.381
Because I have something
to tell him.

35:54.214 --> 35:55.756
What do you have to tell him?

35:57.172 --> 35:58.714
The man said to only tell him.

36:01.464 --> 36:03.589
The man? What man?

36:08.714 --> 36:09.923
What man, Jessa?

36:11.506 --> 36:14.589
(CAR DOOR OPENS, CLOSES)

36:29.172 --> 36:30.506
HOWARD: Hey, guys.

36:30.589 --> 36:32.089
Can we talk out here first?

36:32.172 --> 36:35.297
-This is my wife, Jeannie.
-I know who she is.

36:35.381 --> 36:36.506
(RALPH CLEARS THROAT)

36:36.589 --> 36:38.005
Thank you for coming by,

36:38.089 --> 36:39.506
but it's just because
my daughter

36:39.589 --> 36:41.255
had a bad dream involving you.

36:42.297 --> 36:43.756
Oh, I'm--
I'm sorry to hear that.

36:44.673 --> 36:45.798
And she thinks that she has

36:45.881 --> 36:47.214
to tell you something
about the dream.

36:47.297 --> 36:50.005
And my hope is if you come in
and let her...

36:50.089 --> 36:51.756
that maybe it will help ease
her mind.

36:54.422 --> 36:56.756
I need you to help ease
her mind, okay?

36:58.172 --> 36:59.172
Yeah.

37:13.130 --> 37:14.130
(DOOR CLOSES)

37:15.631 --> 37:17.464
RALPH:
That must have been a very...

37:17.547 --> 37:18.756
scary dream, Jessa.

37:20.130 --> 37:23.923
JESSA: It wasn't a dream.
I said that ten times!

37:24.005 --> 37:25.464
GLORY: It was, my love.

37:25.547 --> 37:27.964
If there was a man here,
he couldn't have gotten upstairs

37:28.047 --> 37:29.506
without one of us seeing him.

37:30.339 --> 37:31.881
Or hearing him.

37:31.964 --> 37:34.422
You know, we have creaky stairs.

37:34.506 --> 37:36.005
RALPH:
But what makes you so sure

37:36.089 --> 37:37.172
that it wasn't a dream, Jessa?

37:37.255 --> 37:39.839
Can you just do
what I asked you to do, please?

37:41.464 --> 37:42.506
RALPH: Yeah.

37:43.089 --> 37:44.589
Um...

37:44.673 --> 37:46.464
But you know whatever it was,

37:46.547 --> 37:50.089
you know there's no man
up there now, right?

37:50.172 --> 37:52.547
Not now, but he said he wouldn't
come back

37:52.631 --> 37:54.005
if I gave you the message.

37:56.589 --> 37:57.923
Okay.

37:58.005 --> 37:59.172
What's the message?

38:01.422 --> 38:02.964
He said to tell you to stop.

38:06.255 --> 38:07.297
Stop what?

38:10.798 --> 38:11.923
He said if you don't stop,

38:12.005 --> 38:14.714
something very bad
is going to... happen.

38:20.631 --> 38:22.923
Did he say what kind of bad
thing was going to happen?

38:23.005 --> 38:24.673
GLORY: Okay, time to go
upstairs. (CLEARS THROAT)

38:24.756 --> 38:25.839
Come on. Come on.

38:29.547 --> 38:31.464
Goddamnit, Ralph.
Thanks for nothing.

38:31.547 --> 38:33.756
Glory, can I talk to you
for a second?

38:33.839 --> 38:36.255
-Just the two of us?
-(GLORY SIGHS)

38:46.297 --> 38:48.339
HOWARD: So how did you find
Holly Gibney?

38:53.089 --> 38:56.839
Um... I found her unique.

38:57.673 --> 39:00.339
-"Unique," he says.
-Mm.

39:00.422 --> 39:02.798
She's a full-tilt
bull goose loony...

39:03.881 --> 39:05.381
but she's damn good
at what she does.

39:06.381 --> 39:07.422
You'll see.

39:15.047 --> 39:17.255
When our son Derek
was Jessa's age,

39:17.339 --> 39:18.923
he used to have
a lot of nightmares.

39:20.047 --> 39:22.839
And Ralph and I,
we discovered that...

39:22.923 --> 39:24.798
just saying,
"Oh, it's a bad dream,"

39:24.881 --> 39:26.839
didn't really help him
very much.

39:26.923 --> 39:29.589
In fact, it usually made him
more agitated.

39:30.964 --> 39:32.047
Your point?

39:33.756 --> 39:35.589
But if we tried to see it
through his eyes,

39:35.673 --> 39:37.923
if we took it as seriously
as he did,

39:38.005 --> 39:40.089
you know,
and asked him details about it

39:40.172 --> 39:42.923
or his thoughts about
what it all meant,

39:43.005 --> 39:46.047
a lot of the times he would
end up convincing himself

39:46.130 --> 39:48.255
that it was just nothing more
than a crappy dream.

39:49.381 --> 39:51.381
Either that,
or he'd end up so bored

39:51.464 --> 39:54.047
by our little debriefing session
that he'd fall back asleep,

39:54.130 --> 39:55.798
just to get us out
of the room.

39:57.798 --> 39:59.339
So, my point...

39:59.422 --> 40:00.798
telling you this is just...

40:02.297 --> 40:04.172
maybe it's not so terrible if...

40:06.297 --> 40:09.839
Can you just let Ralph keep
asking Jessa about her dream?

40:11.798 --> 40:12.798
No.

40:16.464 --> 40:17.464
But you can.

40:21.130 --> 40:22.756
JEANNIE: So, Jessa...

40:22.839 --> 40:25.798
this man that you saw, can you
tell me what he looked like?

40:26.506 --> 40:27.839
JESSA: Better.

40:27.923 --> 40:30.297
-JEANNIE: Better than...
-JESSA: The other times.

40:33.005 --> 40:34.506
How many times have
you seen him?

40:37.839 --> 40:40.255
-Four.
-GLORY: Oh, honey.

40:40.339 --> 40:43.255
The first time he looked
like daddy but wasn't.

40:43.339 --> 40:44.464
Why didn't you tell me?

40:44.547 --> 40:46.964
Because I thought you would
start crying again,

40:47.047 --> 40:48.923
and I didn't want you to.

40:49.005 --> 40:51.547
JEANNIE: He looked like
your daddy, but he wasn't?

40:51.631 --> 40:54.422
His skin was wrong.
And he was mean.

40:54.506 --> 40:56.255
JEANNIE: How was he mean?

40:56.339 --> 40:58.923
He was trying to make me cry.

40:59.005 --> 41:02.589
What a jerk.
How about the second time?

41:02.673 --> 41:03.839
The second time

41:03.923 --> 41:06.339
he looked just a little bit
like my daddy, but...

41:08.047 --> 41:09.047
messy.

41:09.130 --> 41:11.381
Messy?
You mean like his clothes?

41:12.839 --> 41:17.255
His face. It was blurry.
Like someone tried to erase it.

41:18.964 --> 41:21.047
And did he say anything to you
that time?

41:22.589 --> 41:24.214
Just more mean stuff.

41:25.381 --> 41:27.547
And then you saw him again
last night?

41:27.631 --> 41:29.589
Yeah,
but he wasn't blurry anymore.

41:29.673 --> 41:31.964
Right, you said he was better,
but did he still

41:32.047 --> 41:33.381
look like your daddy?

41:34.214 --> 41:35.214
No way.

41:35.881 --> 41:37.506
This time...

41:37.589 --> 41:40.589
he was more muscly
here and here...

41:41.381 --> 41:42.839
and he looked inky.

41:44.172 --> 41:45.214
Inky?

41:47.881 --> 41:50.964
I'm tired. I don't want to
answer anymore.

41:51.047 --> 41:54.964
Okay, well, now that you gave
Mr. Anderson the message

41:55.047 --> 41:57.297
I don't think he's ever
coming back, do you?

41:57.381 --> 41:59.839
-He said he wouldn't.
-And if he does,

41:59.923 --> 42:01.714
tell him to bug off.

42:01.798 --> 42:05.214
Tell him, if he has a message
he wants to give me,

42:05.297 --> 42:08.089
he can give it to me himself.
Okay, Jessa?

42:09.172 --> 42:10.881
I don't think you want that.

42:11.923 --> 42:13.047
You remember, honey,

42:13.130 --> 42:16.255
that he can't hurt you,
so you don't have to be scared.

42:16.339 --> 42:18.339
JESSA:
He doesn't make me scared,

42:18.422 --> 42:20.839
he makes me angry.

42:20.923 --> 42:23.756
I think you're the one
who's supposed to be scared.

42:29.547 --> 42:30.631
RALPH: Mm.

42:38.464 --> 42:41.422
♪ (SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

43:07.798 --> 43:08.923
GLORY: Okay, guys.

43:10.464 --> 43:11.506
Grab your jackets.

43:13.839 --> 43:15.631
I wanna be done by the time
Daddy gets back

43:15.714 --> 43:17.005
from visiting Grandpa.

43:19.714 --> 43:20.923
-MAYA: Mom?
-GLORY: Yes.

43:21.005 --> 43:22.339
I made you a picture.

43:23.589 --> 43:24.673
JESSA: Momma...

43:25.756 --> 43:27.964
I made a new picture for Daddy.

43:28.047 --> 43:29.214
A baseball man.

43:29.297 --> 43:30.339
GLORY: Nice.

43:33.214 --> 43:34.297
(DOOR CLOSES)

44:00.506 --> 44:03.547
♪ (COUNTRY MUSIC
PLAYS ON STEREO) ♪

44:34.964 --> 44:36.214
Your car get towed?

44:36.297 --> 44:37.547
No, I'm just looking
for the person

44:37.631 --> 44:38.923
who's in charge
of mall security.

44:40.214 --> 44:41.255
That would be me.

44:43.130 --> 44:44.172
One of my people

44:44.255 --> 44:45.923
decided to use a Taser
on her husband last night,

44:46.005 --> 44:47.422
they've been going
through a rough patch,

44:47.506 --> 44:49.631
so it left me
shorthanded for today.

44:54.339 --> 44:56.589
Now that you've got me,
how can I help you?

45:12.673 --> 45:14.214
ANDY KATCAVAGE:
What dates were you looking for?

45:14.297 --> 45:15.631
HOLLY:
March 6th to the 11th.

45:16.172 --> 45:17.214
(ANDY MUTTERS)

45:17.297 --> 45:18.881
That's six weeks ago.

45:18.964 --> 45:21.214
We scrub the surveillance
cameras in this parking lot

45:21.297 --> 45:23.255
-once every five days.
-Figured as much.

45:23.798 --> 45:25.297
Thought I'd take a shot.

45:26.297 --> 45:27.881
Have you checked
with the Traffic Division?

45:27.964 --> 45:29.547
HOLLY:
It was never reported stolen.

45:29.631 --> 45:30.673
ANDY: Oh.

45:31.422 --> 45:32.464
Excuse me.

45:33.255 --> 45:35.381
Ma'am, you can't park there.

45:35.464 --> 45:36.798
There's two spots, right there.

45:37.547 --> 45:38.589
Thank you.

45:40.172 --> 45:41.130
I can, uh...

45:41.214 --> 45:43.005
I can ask my buddy over
at the impound yard,

45:43.089 --> 45:44.172
see if it turned up over there?

45:44.255 --> 45:47.047
The van was in the custody
of Cherokee City PD.

45:47.130 --> 45:49.339
I was hoping I could get eyes
on the individual

45:49.422 --> 45:51.506
who might have
taken it from here to there.

45:52.673 --> 45:54.798
Sorry. Can I ask why
Cherokee City PD?

45:56.130 --> 45:59.005
It was used to abduct a child
who was subsequently murdered.

46:01.005 --> 46:03.297
In any event,
thank you for your help.

46:04.464 --> 46:05.506
You're a PI?

46:06.964 --> 46:08.005
Yes, I am.

46:09.130 --> 46:10.839
Would you like to see
my license?

46:10.923 --> 46:12.214
No, that's okay.

46:13.172 --> 46:14.506
But do you have a business card?

46:16.005 --> 46:17.673
Oh, here.
Here, I'll-- I'll trade you.

46:20.339 --> 46:21.923
You know...

46:22.005 --> 46:24.506
if there's anything else
I can help you with just...

46:24.589 --> 46:26.214
make sure to reach out, okay?

46:34.547 --> 46:37.547
♪ (HIP HOP MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

46:39.172 --> 46:40.422
REYNARD: Mm.

46:40.506 --> 46:42.464
My great grandmother handles
her oil better than this dude.

46:42.547 --> 46:47.506
NATHAN: (CHUCKLES)
Wait for it. Wait for it...

46:51.089 --> 46:52.089
(GROANS)

47:03.130 --> 47:05.673
REYNARD: (LAUGHS) Boom!
Ha! Pay up, fucker.

47:05.756 --> 47:07.214
NATHAN: (MUTTERS)
Tss! Piece of shit.

47:11.172 --> 47:12.214
(GRUNTS)

47:15.589 --> 47:18.422
(INDISTINCT ANNOUNCEMENT
OVER PA)

47:19.005 --> 47:20.047
Jack...

47:21.506 --> 47:23.631
Come on, man,
let's get you some fresh air.

47:23.714 --> 47:24.964
(SCREAMS)

47:25.047 --> 47:28.422
-Goddamnit!
-I ain't touch him.

47:28.506 --> 47:29.381
(JACK GROANS)

47:29.464 --> 47:30.464
REYNARD: I know. I know.

47:30.547 --> 47:31.673
Hey, Jack,
I didn't touch you, man.

47:31.756 --> 47:34.506
JACK: Please, please.
(BREATHES HEAVILY)

47:34.589 --> 47:36.589
(WHISPERS) I'll do anything,
just make it stop.

47:37.381 --> 47:38.422
Just make it stop.

47:39.964 --> 47:41.047
(EXHALES) Please.

47:54.714 --> 47:56.130
(KNOCKING ON DOOR)

47:58.047 --> 48:00.381
Oh, hey. Hi, Glory.

48:00.464 --> 48:02.005
Hi, sorry for just...

48:02.089 --> 48:03.589
showing up like this...

48:03.673 --> 48:05.255
I just, um...

48:06.589 --> 48:08.255
Can I talk to you for a minute?

48:09.589 --> 48:11.422
-Yeah, come in.
-Thank you.

48:15.714 --> 48:17.756
Yeah, thanks. I wanted to...

48:19.673 --> 48:20.964
check in on you, you know,

48:21.047 --> 48:22.673
see how you were doing
after yesterday.

48:24.547 --> 48:25.756
I'm all right.

48:26.798 --> 48:27.798
And Jessa?

48:29.964 --> 48:31.464
She slept through the night.

48:32.130 --> 48:33.339
Oh, excellent.

48:34.130 --> 48:35.130
Good.

48:41.130 --> 48:42.631
I don't have an agenda
coming here,

48:42.714 --> 48:45.130
I really did just wanna
check in on you and the girls.

48:50.506 --> 48:52.506
It was funny yesterday,
you and Jessa.

48:54.381 --> 48:55.381
Funny?

48:57.547 --> 48:59.339
Yeah, it reminded me of...

49:00.756 --> 49:01.798
Maya...

49:03.005 --> 49:05.422
my oldest, when she...

49:05.506 --> 49:06.923
she couldn't have been
more than seven.

49:07.005 --> 49:09.464
She went to a friend's house
for a play date,

49:09.547 --> 49:13.673
and that girl's older brother
made them watch...

49:13.756 --> 49:16.047
a DVD of a horror movie.
Leprechaun.

49:19.005 --> 49:21.130
-Man, I wanted to kill that kid.
-I bet.

49:22.506 --> 49:25.422
And Maya came home
and she was convinced...

49:25.506 --> 49:28.089
that there was a leprechaun
hiding somewhere in the house...

49:29.130 --> 49:30.506
waiting to get her.

49:32.881 --> 49:34.422
And I remember trying
to convince her that

49:34.506 --> 49:37.547
leprechauns don't exist,
but she wasn't buying it.

49:39.422 --> 49:40.839
And then Terry had a go.

49:42.714 --> 49:44.381
And do you know what he said?

49:45.506 --> 49:46.631
What?

49:46.714 --> 49:49.714
He said, "Well, yes, leprechauns
exist but they only live

49:49.798 --> 49:52.631
in Ireland and they're forbidden
to leave the country."

49:52.714 --> 49:53.881
(BOTH CHUCKLE)

49:53.964 --> 49:56.714
And she said, "Oh, okay, good."
And then that was that.

49:58.547 --> 49:59.839
(SIGHS)

49:59.923 --> 50:02.005
He was such a good dad.

50:02.714 --> 50:03.714
(SOBS)

50:04.589 --> 50:05.673
He really was.

50:06.923 --> 50:08.005
(GLORY SNIFFLES)

50:18.714 --> 50:20.047
How do you live with it,
Jeannie?

50:20.964 --> 50:22.047
(GLORY SNIFFS)

50:23.255 --> 50:24.422
I really need to know.

50:33.130 --> 50:35.422
Well, yeah, it's impossible.

50:51.130 --> 50:52.589
ANGELA KELLY: Hey there,
how can I help you?

50:52.673 --> 50:54.381
HOLLY: Um, I'm here to visit,
uh, Peter Maitland.

50:54.464 --> 50:56.005
ANGELA: Okay,
are you a member of the family?

50:56.089 --> 50:57.714
HOLLY:
I'm a friend of the family.

50:57.798 --> 51:00.547
ANGELA: Uh, I'm sorry
that won't do. LSC policy.

51:00.631 --> 51:01.881
HOLLY: Can I ask how he's doing?

51:01.964 --> 51:04.464
ANGELA: Uh, I cannot give out
that information. Melanie?

51:05.422 --> 51:06.547
When I was very young,

51:06.631 --> 51:08.255
he and my father
were best friends,

51:08.339 --> 51:12.089
and when my parents died,
he and his wife took me in

51:12.172 --> 51:13.381
and raised me as their own.

51:13.464 --> 51:15.172
Also, I drove here
all the way from Chicago.

51:15.255 --> 51:17.297
ANGELA: I'm sorry, I--
I still can't let you up there.

51:17.381 --> 51:19.089
and even if I could,
I have to tell you,

51:19.172 --> 51:20.422
he wouldn't recognize you.

51:21.297 --> 51:23.714
I mean,
he's been going downhill...

51:23.798 --> 51:26.297
rather fast recently, and...

51:26.381 --> 51:27.839
when Alzheimer's is involved,

51:27.923 --> 51:29.881
-they usually--
-How recent?

51:29.964 --> 51:31.964
I would say
in the last month or so.

51:32.047 --> 51:34.005
Early March. Um...

51:34.089 --> 51:36.714
Did something particular
happen back then?

51:41.297 --> 51:42.422
And here I was thinking

51:42.506 --> 51:44.214
I had seen the last
of you people.

51:44.297 --> 51:46.214
HOLLY: Uh, what people?

51:46.297 --> 51:49.881
Fine, play me for a fool.
Reporters, honey, reporters.

51:49.964 --> 51:51.964
-I'm not a reporter.
-Of course not.

51:52.047 --> 51:53.923
Pete Maitland's just the prince
who raised you

51:54.005 --> 51:55.089
as one of his own children.

51:55.172 --> 51:57.547
I need you to turn around
and exit this building.

51:57.631 --> 51:59.089
And if you won't,
I'll have you escorted out.

51:59.172 --> 52:02.506
-I'm-- I'm not a reporter.
-If you say so.

52:02.589 --> 52:05.005
Nonetheless, if you want to see
that old man you will have to

52:05.089 --> 52:07.255
come back with his son
and have him vouch for you.

52:07.339 --> 52:08.255
Come back with Terry Maitland?

52:08.339 --> 52:09.589
ANGELA:
You know, and here's the thing:

52:09.673 --> 52:11.047
Even if I had fallen
for your story

52:11.130 --> 52:12.923
I-- I don't know what you think
you could squeeze out

52:13.005 --> 52:14.881
of that poor man.
Ask the detectives,

52:14.964 --> 52:16.798
they tried talking
to him for weeks.

52:16.881 --> 52:17.964
Talk to him about what?

52:18.047 --> 52:19.881
-Please make sure she leaves.
-I'm going.

52:26.047 --> 52:27.130
(PHONE DIALS)

52:27.214 --> 52:29.297
-RALPH: Hello?
-Holly Gibney.

52:29.381 --> 52:30.964
Ah! Well, hello there,
Holly Gibney.

52:31.047 --> 52:32.631
I don't know who I'm supposed to
report to:

52:32.714 --> 52:35.130
you, Alec or Howard Saloman.

52:35.214 --> 52:37.839
RALPH: Um... You know what,
any of us is fine.

52:37.923 --> 52:40.130
HOLLY: I spoke to the woman at
the center's reception desk.

52:40.214 --> 52:42.047
She wouldn't let me see
Maitland's father,

52:42.130 --> 52:43.589
because she thought
I was a reporter.

52:43.673 --> 52:44.798
Apparently,
a bunch of reporters

52:44.881 --> 52:46.964
showed up about a month ago.
Detectives, too.

52:47.047 --> 52:48.839
Ah, I thought it was
in regards to Terry,

52:48.923 --> 52:50.297
because that was
more or less

52:50.381 --> 52:52.255
the time that the family
was there last time.

52:52.339 --> 52:54.589
But she didn't even know
he was dead.

52:54.673 --> 52:56.923
RALPH: Well, you know,
Cherokee City isn't exactly

52:57.005 --> 52:58.506
the center of the universe,
so--

52:58.589 --> 52:59.839
That being said,

52:59.923 --> 53:02.130
whatever did happen, the cops
wanted to speak to the old man

53:02.214 --> 53:03.756
as part of the investigation.

53:06.839 --> 53:08.631
You'll be looking into that?

53:08.714 --> 53:11.506
HOLLY: Of course.
That's what I'm here for.

53:11.589 --> 53:16.464
Um... Okay, I'm sorry, I didn't
mean to tell you your job.

53:16.547 --> 53:18.839
HOLLY: I know I could've waited
to call until I had more

53:18.923 --> 53:19.839
hard information.

53:19.923 --> 53:21.089
No, no that's fine.

53:23.255 --> 53:24.673
It's just...

53:24.756 --> 53:26.130
sometimes...

53:26.214 --> 53:28.422
every once in a while, I like to
hear the voice of someone

53:28.506 --> 53:29.589
who's on my side.

53:36.756 --> 53:37.756
I'll call when I have something

53:37.839 --> 53:39.297
with a little more meat
on its bones.

53:40.714 --> 53:42.631
-RALPH: Sure.
-(PHONE BEEPS)

54:06.798 --> 54:09.255
♪ (OMINOUS MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

55:12.339 --> 55:15.714
(CELL DOOR UNLOCKS IN DISTANCE)

55:31.881 --> 55:33.089
(DOOR UNLOCKS)

55:47.631 --> 55:49.214
(DOOR UNLOCKS)

55:50.631 --> 55:52.589
(FOOTSTEPS RETREATING)

55:56.589 --> 55:58.631
♪ (MUSIC INTENSIFIES) ♪

56:48.506 --> 56:49.506
No.

56:50.172 --> 56:51.881
You don't get to do this.

56:51.964 --> 56:53.089
Fuck you, I don't.

57:09.047 --> 57:10.130
(CELL DOOR CLOSES)

57:15.964 --> 57:17.339
JACK: Whatever you need
me to do.

57:21.089 --> 57:22.339
Whatever you need me to do.

57:25.506 --> 57:26.714
Whatever you need me to do.

57:33.714 --> 57:35.964
♪ (OMINOUS MUSIC PLAYS) ♪

59:34.798 --> 59:36.339
(CLOCK TICKING)

59:38.130 --> 59:39.631
(BELL TOLLS)

59:41.172 --> 59:42.839
-(TICKING RAPIDLY)
-(GLASS SHATTERS)

59:42.923 --> 59:45.214
♪ (WOMAN SINGING IN SPANISH) ♪

59:45.297 --> 59:46.381
HOLLY GIBNEY:
Sleep, child.

59:46.464 --> 59:48.589
♪ (SINGING CONTINUES) ♪

59:49.714 --> 59:50.923
Sleep, now.

59:51.297 --> 59:52.631
(SIREN WAILING)

59:53.214 --> 59:55.506
Somewhere on one of those tapes,
there might be

59:55.589 --> 59:56.839
a real game changer.

59:57.631 --> 59:59.089
(CLOCK TICKING)

59:59.172 --> 1:00:00.631
It wasn't him, you know.

1:00:00.881 --> 1:00:03.172
(TICKING RAPIDLY)

1:00:05.839 --> 1:00:08.798
WOMAN: This day and age,
we find it so difficult

1:00:08.881 --> 1:00:11.839
to believe in anything
that we can't explain.

1:00:15.339 --> 1:00:17.506
♪ (MUSIC CONCLUDES) ♪
